30/*
31 * Definitions shared between the configuration parser
32 * and the grammars; not visible to users of the parser.
33 */
34
35/*% Clause may occur multiple times (e.g., "zone") */
36#define CFG_CLAUSEFLAG_MULTI 0x00000001
37/*% Clause is obsolete (logs a warning, but is not a fatal error) */
38#define CFG_CLAUSEFLAG_OBSOLETE 0x00000002
39/*% Clause is not implemented, and may never be */
40#define CFG_CLAUSEFLAG_NOTIMP 0x00000004
41/*% Clause is not implemented yet */
42#define CFG_CLAUSEFLAG_NYI 0x00000008
43/*% Default value has changed since earlier release */
44#define CFG_CLAUSEFLAG_NEWDEFAULT 0x00000010
45/*%
46 * Clause needs to be interpreted during parsing
47 * by calling a callback function, like the
48 * "directory" option.
49 */
50#define CFG_CLAUSEFLAG_CALLBACK 0x00000020
51/*% A option that is only used in testing. */
52#define CFG_CLAUSEFLAG_TESTONLY 0x00000040
53/*% A configuration option that was not configured at compile time. */
54#define CFG_CLAUSEFLAG_NOTCONFIGURED 0x00000080
55/*% A option for a experimental feature. */
56#define CFG_CLAUSEFLAG_EXPERIMENTAL 0x00000100
57/*% A configuration option that is ineffective due to
58 * compile time options, but is harmless. */
59#define CFG_CLAUSEFLAG_NOOP 0x00000200
60/*% Clause will be obsolete in a future release (logs a warning) */
61#define CFG_CLAUSEFLAG_DEPRECATED 0x00000400
62/*% Clause has been obsolete so long that it's now a fatal error */
63#define CFG_CLAUSEFLAG_ANCIENT 0x00000800
64
65/*%
66 * Zone types for which a clause is valid:
67 * These share space with CFG_CLAUSEFLAG values, but count
68 * down from the top.
69 */
70#define CFG_ZONE_MASTER 0x80000000
71#define CFG_ZONE_SLAVE 0x40000000
72#define CFG_ZONE_STUB 0x20000000
73#define CFG_ZONE_HINT 0x10000000
74#define CFG_ZONE_FORWARD 0x08000000
75#define CFG_ZONE_STATICSTUB 0x04000000
76#define CFG_ZONE_REDIRECT 0x02000000
77#define CFG_ZONE_DELEGATION 0x01000000
78#define CFG_ZONE_INVIEW 0x00800000
79#define CFG_ZONE_MIRROR 0x00400000
80

88/*
89 * Function types for configuration object methods
90 */
91
92typedef isc_result_t (*cfg_parsefunc_t)(cfg_parser_t *, const cfg_type_t *type,
93 cfg_obj_t **);
94typedef void (*cfg_printfunc_t)(cfg_printer_t *, const cfg_obj_t *);
95typedef void (*cfg_docfunc_t)(cfg_printer_t *, const cfg_type_t *);
96typedef void (*cfg_freefunc_t)(cfg_parser_t *, cfg_obj_t *);

98/*
99 * Structure definitions
100 */
101
102/*%
103 * A configuration printer object. This is an abstract
104 * interface to a destination to which text can be printed
105 * by calling the function 'f'.
106 */
107struct cfg_printer {
108 void (*f)(void *closure, const char *text, int textlen);
109 void *closure;
110 int indent;
111 int flags;
112};
113
114/*% A clause definition. */
115struct cfg_clausedef {
116 const char *name;
117 cfg_type_t *type;
118 unsigned int flags;
119};
120
121/*% A tuple field definition. */
122struct cfg_tuplefielddef {
123 const char *name;
124 cfg_type_t *type;
125 unsigned int flags;
126};
127
128/*% A configuration object type definition. */
129struct cfg_type {
130 const char *name; /*%< For debugging purposes only */
131 cfg_parsefunc_t parse;
132 cfg_printfunc_t print;
133 cfg_docfunc_t doc; /*%< Print grammar description */
134 cfg_rep_t * rep; /*%< Data representation */
135 const void * of; /*%< Additional data for meta-types */
136};
137
138/*% A keyword-type definition, for things like "port <integer>". */
139typedef struct {
140 const char *name;
141 const cfg_type_t *type;
142} keyword_type_t;
143
144struct cfg_map {
145 cfg_obj_t *id; /*%< Used for 'named maps' like keys, zones, &c */
146 const cfg_clausedef_t * const *clausesets; /*%< The clauses that
147 can occur in this map;
148 used for printing */
149 isc_symtab_t *symtab;
150};
151
152typedef struct cfg_netprefix cfg_netprefix_t;
153
154struct cfg_netprefix {
155 isc_netaddr_t address; /* IP4/IP6 */
156 unsigned int prefixlen;
157};
158
159/*%
160 * A configuration data representation.
161 */
162struct cfg_rep {
163 const char * name; /*%< For debugging only */
164 cfg_freefunc_t free; /*%< How to free this kind of data. */
165};
166
167/*%
168 * A configuration object. This is the main building block
169 * of the configuration parse tree.
170 */
171
172struct cfg_obj {
173 const cfg_type_t *type;
174 union {
175 uint32_t uint32;
176 uint64_t uint64;
177 isc_textregion_t string; /*%< null terminated, too */
178 bool boolean;
179 cfg_map_t map;
180 cfg_list_t list;
181 cfg_obj_t ** tuple;
182 isc_sockaddr_t sockaddr;
183 struct {
184 isc_sockaddr_t sockaddr;
185 isc_dscp_t dscp;
186 } sockaddrdscp;
187 cfg_netprefix_t netprefix;
188 } value;
189 isc_refcount_t references; /*%< reference counter */
190 const char * file;
191 unsigned int line;
192 cfg_parser_t * pctx;
193};
194
195
196/*% A list element. */
197struct cfg_listelt {
198 cfg_obj_t *obj;
199 ISC_LINK(cfg_listelt_t) link;
200};
201
202/*% The parser object. */
203struct cfg_parser {
204 isc_mem_t * mctx;
205 isc_log_t * lctx;
206 isc_lex_t * lexer;
207 unsigned int errors;
208 unsigned int warnings;
209 isc_token_t token;
210
211 /*% We are at the end of all input. */
212 bool seen_eof;
213
214 /*% The current token has been pushed back. */
215 bool ungotten;
216
217 /*%
218 * The stack of currently active files, represented
219 * as a configuration list of configuration strings.
220 * The head is the top-level file, subsequent elements
221 * (if any) are the nested include files, and the
222 * last element is the file currently being parsed.
223 */
224 cfg_obj_t * open_files;
225
226 /*%
227 * Names of files that we have parsed and closed
228 * and were previously on the open_file list.
229 * We keep these objects around after closing
230 * the files because the file names may still be
231 * referenced from other configuration objects
232 * for use in reporting semantic errors after
233 * parsing is complete.
234 */
235 cfg_obj_t * closed_files;
236
237 /*%
238 * Name of a buffer being parsed; used only for
239 * logging.
240 */
241 char const * buf_name;
242
243 /*%
244 * Current line number. We maintain our own
245 * copy of this so that it is available even
246 * when a file has just been closed.
247 */
248 unsigned int line;
249
250 /*%
251 * Parser context flags, used for maintaining state
252 * from one token to the next.
253 */
254 unsigned int flags;
255
256 /*%< Reference counter */
257 isc_refcount_t references;
258
259 cfg_parsecallback_t callback;
260 void *callbackarg;
261};
262
263/* Parser context flags */
264#define CFG_PCTX_SKIP 0x1
265#define CFG_PCTX_NODEPRECATED 0x2
